  "final_analysis": "Steroids are used in the treatment of certain forms of tuberculosis primarily for their anti-inflammatory effects and, in some cases, for hormone replacement. In tuberculosis meningitis, steroids help reduce inflammation of the meninges, which is crucial to prevent serious complications such as brain damage. In tuberculosis pericarditis, steroids are used to reduce the inflammation of the pericardium, thereby preventing constrictive pericarditis. In cases of adrenal involvement in tuberculosis, which can lead to adrenal insufficiency, steroids serve as a critical hormone replacement therapy. However, in ileo-caecal tuberculosis, which primarily involves the ileum and caecum parts of the gastrointestinal tract, the primary treatment involves anti-tuberculosis medications and potentially surgery to manage complications like obstruction or perforation. Steroids do not play a central role in the management of ileo-caecal tuberculosis as the condition does not primarily involve issues that steroids are used to address, such as significant inflammation or hormone deficiency. This aligns with medical consensus and is supported by standard treatment guidelines.",
